GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks

metadata.name: Chaos Culture #263
metadata.description:
"Chaos Culture" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

„ÄäË•øÈÅäË®ò„ÄãÁ¨¨‰∏ÄÂõû:„ÄåÊ∑∑Ê≤åÊú™ÂàÜÂ§©Âú∞‰∫ÇÔºåËå´Ëå´Ê∏∫Ê∏∫ÁÑ°‰∫∫Ë¶ã„ÄÇ„Äç

Chaos Culture is the final chapter of this series. There is a legend in the East that before Pan Gu opened up the sky and created the earth, the world was a chaotic place, and no one knew its appearance. And I have always been fascinated by this mythical story since he was a child.

These three works have a father-son relationship, Research > Memory > Culture, with each work re-growing through the remnants of the previous work, depending on its image. From the beginning of the creative coding, I like the concept of recursion the most. Here I experiment with my central thinking through this iterative relationship so that the work is not only the shadow of the artist but also the pulling force of repetition.

"Ê∑∑Ê≤å" Chaos in Eastern culture represents the initial state of things. This state is consistent with what we believe in generative art: Anything can happen if different forces are applied. Letting chaos grow out of order and then destroying it, the iterative process, is like my usual dialogue with myself, and maybe it's all just a diary.

Through these three series of works, whether I can eventually find everything in my childhood fantasy, I am not sure yet. The only thing I can be sure of is that I will continue to explore.

- Click the mouse to save an artwork.
- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.

Artist: Aluan Wang (ileivoivm).
Made with p5js and glsl.

metadata.name: Asterium #145
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnem√ºhle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: New World #132
metadata.description:
A New World can form out of destruction or creation.

Inspiration: 
The forms that appear in New World evoke cliffs, islands, and other natural structures, but perspective distortions bend them into a surreal and new computational reality. 

The collection was in part influenced by my feelings during the first two weeks of the invasion of Ukraine. It was a time marked by anxiety, uncertainty, and disillusionment. But, New World was also inspired by the hope embodied in my creative process and the genart community. Hence, the collection takes on a double meaning: a new world can form out of destruction or creation. 

Algorithm:
The collection is completely generative and written with p5.js. It began as an exploration of the dual contouring algorithm and purposefully builds on a bug I introduced when filling the contours by selecting vertices out of winding order. 

Pricing:
Dutch Auction: 16xtz -> 12xtz -> 8xtz decreasing every 10 minutes.

Charity:
5% of the primary sales will be donated to Ukrainian humanitarian aid funds through the contract set up by @ciphrd and @Veqtor.

Controls:
Key ‚Äôs‚Äô: Save an image of the output at the current resolution (available once the piece has finished generating)
Key ‚ÄòArrow Up‚Äô & ‚ÄòArrow Down‚Äô: Cycle through resolution scaling factors at increments of 1080p. 1080p is the minimum resolution. There is no maximum resolution but loading performance will worsen at higher scaling
Key ‚Äòo‚Äô: Toggle the land outlines on or off

Browser Support:
Confirmed to work on desktop browsers (Chrome Version 99.0.4844.51, Safari v15.3, Firefox v98.0) and Safari iOS v14.8

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #41
metadata.description:
‚ÄúOrdinary Places‚Äù is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher‚Äôs ‚ÄúWater Tower‚Äù photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha‚Äôs ‚Äú26 Gasoline Stations‚Äù photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather‚Äôs farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Knockout #20
metadata.description:
An exploration of screen printing techniques and how these effects can be achieved in generative work. The halftone effect works by placing very small dots next to each other to give the illusion of new shades and hues. Each Knockout samples three colors for the main composition and runs small sections of the canvas back through the machine after shuffling the base palette. The secondary passes vary in size, creating interesting emergent patterns on the overlap.

Press 's' in live view to save a .png

Built and tested with Chrome on Apple silicon. Some outputs may take up to 20s on slower machines.

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: AUTOJOURNEYPAINT #156
metadata.description:
An automatic painting journey

AUTOJOURNEYPAINT  uses a series of custom built walkers to make plots with a great variety of properties, including packing gaps, directions and propensity for turning. These plots are then drawn over with varying, incremented pixel brushes.

AUTOJOURNEYPAINT chooses color for itself from a broad list of more than 100 colors. It selects a palette of 8 but might not use all of them.

The background consists of a single color at the back and then one channel (either r, g, b) of the same color iterating from 0 to 255 while also iterating over a number of pixels within a border, all fixed to a pixel grid of variable size. The iteration over pixel numbers means the background produces very different patterns at different screen sizes

If you want to know more about the variables used they are output in the console log

Responsive to screen size. Larger resolutions will implement more brush strokes.

Some renders may be slower due to more complex collision detection in some brush settings.

Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the image as a png.

metadata.name: Meet Arty #178
metadata.description:
Future royalties are shared 50% with the original minters!

Who is Arty?

Arty is the name given to this symbol by the friendly folks of Newberry, South Carolina. The symbol itself can be seen carved into the architectural moulding of the Old Newberry Hotel (est. 1878). No one knows why, when or by whom the symbol was created but many of the artists of Newberry Made have adopted it as their maker‚Äôs mark. Learn more about us at www.NewberryMade.com. 

#NewberryIsAnArtTown

Why is there a Red Dot in the bottom corner?

The red dot is my signature for an ongoing series of generative art on fxhash (a shout-out to my first project). I will continue to utilize red dots as a design element in future work.

About the token

- The canvas is square and responsive based on your viewport
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save (image file type is SVG)
- Owners will be given priority access to future reserve lists
- Coded using p5js & SVGCanvas v2.0.3


About the Artist

Robert Matheson is a community engaged artist from Newberry, South Carolina. His work is focused on improving the health and well-being of others through the arts. In 2019 Robert established Newberry Made, a local artist & maker registry that has grown to over 190 members.

Robert's most recent creation is the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. A creative space focused on providing NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition to help artists and the broader community benefit from emerging digital economies. Learn more at www.RobertMatheson.com and www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: Stepping Stones #128
metadata.description:
"Stepping Stones" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022

Stepping Stones explores the idea that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts. Simple patterns, shapes, textures, and colors are arranged in randomly selected ways. Overlaying shapes distort and blend, breaking these objects apart and causing complex forms to emerge. Combining these individual features together results in varying outcomes, from surprisingly simple to wildly chaotic.

---------------

Controls:
Press 1-6 to change the scale of the canvas (1 = default, 2500px x 2500px, 6 = 15,000px x 15,000px)
S (or double tap on mobile): Save output at current size
C: Toggle cutout shapes visibility
H: Toggle cutout outlines visibility
B: Iterate border sizes (none, default, 1.5x, 2x, 3x)
T: Toggle texture visibility
F: Toggle fullscreen
Add the url params x and y to set custom dimensions. For example, add &x=1500&y=500 for a 1500px x 500px image

metadata.name: Act One #13
metadata.description:
Act One, where the mannequin says ‚Äútake me home and I will dance for you forever‚Äù.

This work is an exploration of using motion capture data to create digital paintings, and a little belated birthday ballet for #fxhashturnsone. 
20% of primary sales are donated to Three.js.
 
Keyboard Controls:
[P] Play / pause the dance. By default the dance is paused after a few seconds to render a painting.
[S] Save the current view (live mode).
[V] Capture a short webm video (live mode).

Mouse Controls (while dancing): 
[left drag] Rotate
[scroll] Zoom
[right drag] Pan
[right click] Save image

Best viewed in a desktop browser. The output may be different from the preview image if your frame rate is low, reducing the size of the browser window can help improve the frame rate.

Made using Three.js, canvas API and WebGL2.
The 3D model is based on https://sketchfab.com/3d-models/mannequin-dances-ballet-a24678a81a6f4b6d8f8ba0eb1a78e58b, using motion capture data from dancedb.eu. 
Test in Chrome v107.0.5304.107 and Safari v16.1.
